Troubleshooting Tips
Issue: Data files not generating

Verify Python script has execute permissions: chmod +x scripts/*.py
Check virtual environment is activated: source threat-env/bin/activate
Ensure output directories exist: mkdir -p data/{telemetry,network}
Issue: JSON parsing errors

Validate JSON syntax: python3 -m json.tool < file.json
Check file encoding is UTF-8
Verify file is not empty or corrupted
Issue: Missing MITRE ATT&CK technique mappings

Ensure technique IDs follow format: T####
Verify technique exists in MITRE ATT&CK framework
Check technique dictionary is properly initialized
Issue: Alerts not generating

Verify alert thresholds in configuration
Check log file permissions: chmod 644 logs/*.log
Ensure changes exceed threshold values
Conclusion
This lab demonstrated how to integrate real-world security data into dynamic threat models. You learned to automate threat intelligence workflows, analyze attack patterns using the MITRE ATT&CK framework, and generate actionable security recommendations. These skills are essential for maintaining effective security postures in evolving threat landscapes.

Key takeaways:

Threat models must evolve with new data inputs
Automation enables continuous threat intelligence
MITRE ATT&CK provides standardized attack pattern classification
Change detection and alerting enable proactive security responses
Visualization aids in communicating threat intelligence to stakeholders
In production environments, extend this workflow by integrating with SIEM platforms, threat intelligence feeds, and automated response systems.
